This commit adds a method nearly identical to PingV2Registry,
except it uses a POST request instead of a GET request. This is
so that registries that use a proxy that perform authentication on
POST requests but not GET requests (to allow for anonymous pulls)
are able to provide this functionality. Previously, using a GET request
meant there was no way to differentiate if the action being taken was
a push or pull and handle it differently, this allows that.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/galenguyer/moby/commits/c7c6ad1e2fa85567825822f2bc4572e7890b122c"}]

PR #48382: Update the use of setAlpha/setBeta for Cudnn frontend APIs

Imported from GitHub PR https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/48382

The Cudnn frontend APIs overload the setAlpha/setBeta to allow either float or double parameters. The backend stores two copies of the value and will pick the value of correct data type when the build() is called.

This PR follows this behavior and simplifies the usage.

cc. @nluehr

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but
for now it's easier to iterate on the duplicates.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802"},{"sha":"03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"[SSR2 Fixture] Update APIs (#21688)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2"},{"sha":"f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Use npm lockfile for fixture","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c"},{"sha":"c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Remove unused variable","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c"},{"sha":"6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add missing package lock","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849"},{"sha":"a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Fix fixture lockfile manually","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063"}]

[{"sha":"4329740862c41933ba30e2867e9e1b5c66fa5f57","author":{"name":"Galen Guyer","email":"dacd809faff28866c19d048723eb0bfdc6c15e7a@galenguyer.com"},"message":"Add a PostV2Registry method for push authorization

This commit adds a method nearly identical to PingV2Registry,
except it uses a POST request instead of a GET request. This is
so that registries that use a proxy that perform authentication on
POST requests but not GET requests (to allow for anonymous pulls)
are able to provide this functionality. Previously, using a GET request
meant there was no way to differentiate if the action being taken was
a push or pull and handle it differently, this allows that.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/galenguyer/moby/commits/4329740862c41933ba30e2867e9e1b5c66fa5f57"}]

[{"sha":"ecf68d9f189b5d691ae6cacfcc1e150e438d2231","author":{"name":"James Peach","email":"cfb385863e43a54966ce6ee8158f84aabd7009b9@konghq.com"},"message":"feat(*) add reference documentation generator (#2140)

* feat(*) add reference documentation generator

Add tooling to generate CLI reference documentation to the path named
in "$DESTDIR". The goal is for the website to generate reference docs
on each new version.

Per discussion in kuma-website#447, generate the command documentation
locally (as a side-effect of `make check`).

Disable the timestamp on the generated docs, because if we allow cobra to
emit the timestamp , then the docs change every time we run `make check`,
which is undesirable.

This updates kumahq/kuma-website#447.

Signed-off-by: James Peach <james.peach@konghq.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/ecf68d9f189b5d691ae6cacfcc1e150e438d2231"}]

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but
for now it's easier to iterate on the duplicates.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802"},{"sha":"03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"[SSR2 Fixture] Update APIs (#21688)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2"},{"sha":"f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Use npm lockfile for fixture","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c"},{"sha":"c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Remove unused variable","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c"},{"sha":"6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add missing package lock","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849"},{"sha":"a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Fix fixture lockfile manually","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063"}]

Add tooling to generate CLI reference documentation to the path named
in "$DESTDIR". The goal is for the website to generate reference docs
on each new version.

locally (as a side-effect of `make check`).

emit the timestamp , then the docs change every time we run `make check`,
which is undesirable.

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

'one_hot' will automatically uprank the last dimension of your input if necessesary,
and create an encoding for every element in the batch individually. By adding this
explicit output_mode, we can remove the implicit behavior where output_mode='multi_hot'
would uprank all vector inputs and effectively one hot encode them. This allows
'multi_hot' and 'count' encoding unbatched multi-dimensional samples in a
tf.data.Dataset.

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but

Deferring a hidden tree is only supported in Concurrent Mode.

The missing check leads to an infinite loop when an update is scheduled
inside a hidden tree, because the pending work never gets reset.

This "accidentally" worked in the old reconciler because the heurstic
we used to detect offscreen trees was if `childExpirationTime`
was `Never`.

In the new reconciler, we check the tag instead. Which means we also
need to check the mode, like we do in the begin phase.

We should move this check out of the hot path. It shouldn't have been
in the hot path of the old reconciler, either.

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but
for now it's easier to iterate on the duplicates.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802"},{"sha":"03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"[SSR2 Fixture] Update APIs (#21688)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2"},{"sha":"f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Use npm lockfile for fixture","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c"},{"sha":"c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Remove unused variable","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c"},{"sha":"6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add missing package lock","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849"},{"sha":"a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Fix fixture lockfile manually","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MichaelDeBoey/react/commits/a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063"}]

[{"sha":"d0e01d7e235b9abb48137e11462448b6e9442ec0","author":{"name":"Yang Chen","email":"b1c859b0203793580f6fafdc9e88d8c10428cc59@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Read from local in-process workers if one exists.

Added `target_workers` param to `data_service_ops.from_dataset_id` and
`data_service_ops.distribute`. Users can specify "AUTO", "ANY", or
"LOCAL" (case insensitive). If "AUTO", tf.data service runtime decides
which workers to read from. If "ANY", TF workers read from any tf.data
service workers. If "LOCAL", TF workers will only read from local
in-processs tf.data service workers. "AUTO" works well for most cases,
while users can specify other targets. For example, "LOCAL" would help
avoid RPCs and data copy if every TF worker colocates with a tf.data
service worker. Currently, "AUTO" reads from any tf.data service
workers to preserve existing behavior. The default value is "AUTO".

Now TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass can merge resource reads and assigns with
TPUExecute when there are non-interfering resource accesses between read/assigns
and TPUExecute. Interference is checked with resource alias analysis, and now
the pass is a `PerFunctionAggregateAnalysisConsumerPass`.
Previously, the pass was too conservative and considered any resource access as
potentially interfering so in many valid cases we couldn't merge.
Also added tests, made terminology more consistent, and added debug messages.

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't

Added `target_workers` param to `data_service_ops.from_dataset_id` and
`data_service_ops.distribute`. Users can specify "AUTO", "ANY", or
"LOCAL" (case insensitive). If "AUTO", tf.data service runtime decides
which workers to read from. If "ANY", TF workers read from any tf.data
service workers. If "LOCAL", TF workers will only read from local
in-processs tf.data service workers. "AUTO" works well for most cases,
while users can specify other targets. For example, "LOCAL" would help
avoid RPCs and data copy if every TF worker colocates with a tf.data
service worker. Currently, "AUTO" reads from any tf.data service
workers to preserve existing behavior. The default value is "AUTO".

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but

Copy-on isn't impossible, although there are a lot of subtleties if we wanted to do it well (e.g. gradients) in addition to performance issues. It seems reasonably usable without implicit copy-on, so it makes sense to trial without it for now.

Some fiddling with ImmediateExecutionTensorHandle::DebugString to make it more useful for an error message. Removes the TensorHandle override since it's much less useful.

Copy-on isn't impossible, although there are a lot of subtleties if we wanted to do it well (e.g. gradients) in addition to performance issues. It seems reasonably usable without implicit copy-on, so it makes sense to trial without it for now.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rizalgowandy/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

[{"sha":"7550b3d57605eacd6ce118d04a7c2ce3232e7039","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"6d801fb2355a07c9e004ea4635b4ce3edfe405d7@koyeb.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

[{"sha":"229dbc8809b5adb15dda48755a4ecae6a035a5fa","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"6d801fb2355a07c9e004ea4635b4ce3edfe405d7@koyeb.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

Need this to unblock www. Not sure yet how we'll support this properly
long term.

While adding this, I noticed that the normal "hidden" mode of
LegacyHidden doesn't work properly because it doesn't toggle the
visibility of newly inserted nodes. This is fine for now since we only
use it via a userspace abstraction that wraps the children in an
additional node. But implementing this correctly is required for us
to start using it like a fragment, without the wrapper node.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wyz1210355476/react/commits/95ea8ed47c8a92dd72d43349cdd2f12e6b48292a"},{"sha":"8b3b5c35245b3aa0b2802b51856fe9dad5bcb671","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Bugfix: Missing mode check in resetChildLanes (#18961)

Deferring a hidden tree is only supported in Concurrent Mode.

The missing check leads to an infinite loop when an update is scheduled
inside a hidden tree, because the pending work never gets reset.

This "accidentally" worked in the old reconciler because the heurstic
we used to detect offscreen trees was if `childExpirationTime`
was `Never`.

In the new reconciler, we check the tag instead. Which means we also
need to check the mode, like we do in the begin phase.

We should move this check out of the hot path. It shouldn't have been
in the hot path of the old reconciler, either.

Probably by moving `resetChildLanes` into the switch statement
in ReactFiberCompleteWork.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wyz1210355476/react/commits/8b3b5c35245b3aa0b2802b51856fe9dad5bcb671"},{"sha":"a30a1c6ef3a621a57e9372c8249439dbfd9a7375","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"Transfer actualDuration only once for SuspenseList (#18959)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wyz1210355476/react/commits/a30a1c6ef3a621a57e9372c8249439dbfd9a7375"},{"sha":"64f50c667a778c85dc8f1d56e26d881fada4c85a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Remove disableHiddenPropDeprioritization flag (#18964)

* Wire up DOM legacy build

* Hack to filter extra comments for testing purposes

* Use string concat in renderToString

I think this might be faster. We could probably use a combination of this
technique in the stream too to lower the overhead.

* Error if we can't complete the root synchronously

Maybe this should always error but in the async forms we can just delay
the stream until it resolves so it does have some useful semantics.

In the synchronous form it's never useful though. I'm mostly adding the
error because we're testing this behavior for renderToString specifically.

* Gate memory leak tests of internals

These tests don't translate as is to the new implementation and have been
ported to the Fizz tests separately.

* Enable Fizz legacy mode in stable

* Add wrapper around the ServerFormatConfig for legacy mode

This ensures that we can inject custom overrides without negatively
affecting the new implementation.

This adds another field for static mark up for example.

* Wrap pushTextInstance to avoid emitting comments for text in static markup

* Don't emit static mark up for completed suspense boundaries

Completed and client rendered boundaries are only marked for the client
to take over.

Pending boundaries are still supported in case you stream non-hydratable
mark up.

* Wire up generateStaticMarkup to static API entry points

* Mark as renderer for stable

This shouldn't affect the FB one ideally but it's done with the same build
so let's hope this works.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/dbe3363ccd125f89c25fea234031410408f0df09"},{"sha":"a8f5e77b921c890c215fb1c7e24a06f38598deb1","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove invokeGuardedCallback from commit phase (#21666)

(#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but
for now it's easier to iterate on the duplicates.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802"},{"sha":"03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"[SSR2 Fixture] Update APIs (#21688)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2"},{"sha":"f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Use npm lockfile for fixture","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c"},{"sha":"c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Remove unused variable","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c"},{"sha":"6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add missing package lock","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849"},{"sha":"a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Fix fixture lockfile manually","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mosoft521/react/commits/a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063"},{"sha":"bd0a963445715f2963d4a9e3a0485e56cbe60653","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Throw when `act` is used in production (#21686)

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jamlee-t/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.

included as part of the higher bucket index, rather than the lower.
This was already how the layer was documented but not how it was
behaving.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

Change-Id: I90a8ed9ba482b0b86cf09adcc984d3b5c4b7c02d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/6ecb39e10c4f2bfed5f82a33f8effa6d29a43aa8"},{"sha":"f028df0ba2c1b0b8cbb6e667ded3665153f8d127","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Make TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass less conservative

Now TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass can merge resource reads and assigns with
TPUExecute when there are non-interfering resource accesses between read/assigns
and TPUExecute. Interference is checked with resource alias analysis, and now
the pass is a `PerFunctionAggregateAnalysisConsumerPass`.
Previously, the pass was too conservative and considered any resource access as
potentially interfering so in many valid cases we couldn't merge.
Also added tests, made terminology more consistent, and added debug messages.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Angie3120/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/moby/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

Signed-off-by: Sebastiaan van Stijn <github@gone.nl>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/galenguyer/moby/commits/09191c093645f308e5fbce4275b5cdfefb048a67"},{"sha":"7b071e055716028dc8f45842105cd6ce0ff7db1e","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"pkg/archive: RebaseArchiveEntries(): ignore G110

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

    pkg/archive/copy.go:357:16: G110: Potential DoS vulnerability via decompression bomb (gosec)
                if _, err = io.Copy(rebasedTar, srcTar); err != nil {
                            ^

Ignoring GoSec G110. See https://github.com/securego/gosec/pull/433
and https://cure53.de/pentest-report_opa.pdf, which recommends to
replace io.Copy with io.CopyN7. The latter allows to specify the
maximum number of bytes that should be read. By properly defining
the limit, it can be assured that a GZip compression bomb cannot
easily cause a Denial-of-Service.
After reviewing, this should not affect us, because here we do not
read into memory.

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but

[{"sha":"269dd6ec5da85fc5ca819cfa010ce60dd1c83ec6","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"subtreeFlag warning: Fix legacy suspense false positive (#21388)

Legacy Suspense is weird. We intentionally commit a suspended fiber in
an inconsistent state. If the fiber suspended before it mounted any
effects, then the fiber won't have a PassiveStatic effect flag, which
will trigger the "missing expected subtreeFlag" warning.

To avoid the false positive, we'd need to mark fibers that commit in an
incomplete state, somehow. For now I'll disable the warning in legacy
mode, with the assumption that most of the bugs that would trigger it

[{"sha":"7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"createRoot(..., {hydrate:true}) -> hydrateRoot(...) (#21687)

This adds a new top level API for hydrating a root. It takes the initial
children as part of its constructor. These are unlike other render calls
in that they have to represent what the server sent and they can't be
batched with other updates.

I also changed the options to move the hydrationOptions to the top level
since now these options are all hydration options.

I kept the createRoot one just temporarily to make it easier to codemod
internally but I'm doing a follow up to delete.

As part of this I un-dried a couple of paths. ReactDOMLegacy was intended
to be built on top of the new API but it didn't actually use those root
APIs because there are special paths. It also doesn't actually use most of
the commmon paths since all the options are ignored. It also made it hard
to add only warnings for legacy only or new only code paths.

I also forked the create/hydrate paths because they're subtly different
since now the options are different. The containers are also different
because I now error for comment nodes during hydration which just doesn't
work at all but eventually we'll error for all createRoot calls.

After some iteration it might make sense to break out some common paths but
for now it's easier to iterate on the duplicates.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/7ec4c55971aad644616ca0b040f42410659fe802"},{"sha":"03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"[SSR2 Fixture] Update APIs (#21688)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/03c5314b44dbf280f3008ce7f587e5055e76c6e2"},{"sha":"f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Use npm lockfile for fixture","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/f283d7524ac5c30c5190e1bbe1b047dce4479a0c"},{"sha":"c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Remove unused variable","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/c0a77029c4acb60844108fbbd7f5e960b1d81b7c"},{"sha":"6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add missing package lock","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/6cbf2a8b3b13e5510467158967b85b0013f6f849"},{"sha":"a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Fix fixture lockfile manually","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/a0d2d1e1e1830e35bf12174f3cc273231aa03063"}]

[{"sha":"b780f95ae0af868d146992fa3306e42e84dd3c9c","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp) Clear snapshots from cache on disconnect (#2172)

Previously we were pushing an empty snapshot on the cache when a dp was disconnecting.
This was causing the dp to get an empty snapshot after a restart.
This would cause listeners to disappear for a short time and causing the traffic going through the dp to fail.
We now clear the snapshot from the dp to avoid this behaviour.

Fix #2176

some TF libraries got loaded twice and some global variables got overwritten.

This bug was introduced in de37b1e - TF statically loads a bunch of TF_VARIANT decoders,
but then it dynamically loads the same (or some) libraries and overwrites global lists,
this bug has actually been there forever, but no one uses TF_VARIANT to store bool or int32,
so when those got overwritten (actually, lost), no one cared.

But variant decoder for TensorList got lost and reverting de37b1e should have fixed that.
This patch fixed the bug by explicitly calling single static function defined not in a header, but in C code.

Please see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/44428 for how
this bug was found and which fix worked for macos, the second commit
will fix it for everyone.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pashu123/tensorflow/commits/39812646c944af98ee9ad1c1ce86eb9d57a1aded"},{"sha":"6d6a1d272c73977dd2a1824adf6aff9644190779","author":{"name":"Evgeniy Polyakov","email":"9be07b15919dab1b45f07f962d8e37ba7c50f920@ioremap.net"},"message":"This bug was introduced in 15275d3 - because TF libs got loaded the
second time somewhere in its life cycle (probably dynamically when there
are multiple saved_model models in the same inference environment,
please see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/44428 for
examples and fixes), RTTI changes for every class for every new dynamic
library loading, thus TensorList got different RTTI ID and decoder in
variant->get<VariantTensorDataProto>() refuses to decode protobuf.

You have fixed this for MacOS by reverting to the old behaviour (and for

Change-Id: I90a8ed9ba482b0b86cf09adcc984d3b5c4b7c02d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/6ecb39e10c4f2bfed5f82a33f8effa6d29a43aa8"},{"sha":"f028df0ba2c1b0b8cbb6e667ded3665153f8d127","author":{"name":"Michael Gester","email":"83d127f0cbc4af4bb827dac2517a3f01bb4703b7@google.com"},"message":"Make TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass less conservative

Now TPUMergeVariablesWithExecutePass can merge resource reads and assigns with
TPUExecute when there are non-interfering resource accesses between read/assigns
and TPUExecute. Interference is checked with resource alias analysis, and now
the pass is a `PerFunctionAggregateAnalysisConsumerPass`.
Previously, the pass was too conservative and considered any resource access as
potentially interfering so in many valid cases we couldn't merge.
Also added tests, made terminology more consistent, and added debug messages.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 379611333
Change-Id: Iad64a1968be321b2e66c92181b64acab80d2a4a4","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/c45d90eaaa14352f71fa3371c34b6f9948dd91f6"},{"sha":"d0e01d7e235b9abb48137e11462448b6e9442ec0","author":{"name":"Yang Chen","email":"b1c859b0203793580f6fafdc9e88d8c10428cc59@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Read from local in-process workers if one exists.

Added `target_workers` param to `data_service_ops.from_dataset_id` and
`data_service_ops.distribute`. Users can specify "AUTO", "ANY", or
"LOCAL" (case insensitive). If "AUTO", tf.data service runtime decides
which workers to read from. If "ANY", TF workers read from any tf.data
service workers. If "LOCAL", TF workers will only read from local
in-processs tf.data service workers. "AUTO" works well for most cases,
while users can specify other targets. For example, "LOCAL" would help
avoid RPCs and data copy if every TF worker colocates with a tf.data
service worker. Currently, "AUTO" reads from any tf.data service
workers to preserve existing behavior. The default value is "AUTO".
